## Introduction

The dynamics of the Heston model are given by the following system of stochastic differential equations:

$$
dS_t = \mu S_t \, dt + \sqrt{v_t} S_t \, dW_t^S
$$

$$
dv_t = \kappa(\theta - v_t)\, dt + \sigma \sqrt{v_t} \, dW_t^v
$$

$$
dW_t^S dW_t^v = \rho \, dt
$$

where $S_t$ is the asset price, $v_t$ is the instantaneous variance, $\kappa$ is the rate of mean reversion, $\theta$ is the long-term variance, $\sigma$ is the volatility of volatility, and $\rho$ is the correlation between the asset price and variance processes.

A key challenge in applying the Heston model in practice is calibration, which involves determining model parameters such that model-generated option prices closely match observed market prices.

This can be formulated as:

$$
\min_{\kappa, \theta, \sigma, \rho, v_0} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \left( C_{\text{model}}(K_i, T_i) - C_{\text{market}}(K_i, T_i) \right)^2
$$
